      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: honor plugin auth markers from manifests",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Honor non-secret auth markers supplied by enabled external plugin manifests.\n- Keep marker discovery process-stable, with lifecycle cache clearing on plugin metadata/index writes.\n- Exclude disabled installed plugin roots from fallback manifest scanning so disabled plugins cannot continue to own marker values.\n- Use this branch only as a temporary upstream review vehicle; the durable target is upstream `openclaw/openclaw`.\n\n## Verification\n\n- `git diff --check`\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/agents/model-auth-markers.test.ts src/plugins/manifest-metadata-scan.test.ts`\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs --reporter=verbose src/agents/model-auth-markers.test.ts src/plugins/manifest-metadata-scan.test.ts`\n- `env OPENCLAW_CHECK_CHANGED_REMOTE_CHILD=1 OPENCLAW_CHANGED_LANES_RAW_SYNC=1 CI=1 PNPM_CONFIG_VERIFY_DEPS_BEFORE_RUN=false corepack pnpm check:changed`\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\nBehavior addressed: model/auth marker handling now respects enabled installed external plugin manifest metadata, ignores disabled installed plugin marker metadata, and refreshes marker lookup only through the plugin metadata lifecycle path.\n\nReal environment tested: local OpenClaw source checkout on macOS at PR head `bdc8191cdbd7926f68fc918563a7eeb8cee7a6e0`. The proof used repository production modules for persisted installed-plugin index writes, manifest metadata scanning, lifecycle cache clearing, and model auth marker lookup. No `.dev.vars`, live credentials, or private plugin config were read.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch: `node --import tsx -` with a redacted temp-home script that created enabled and disabled plugin manifests under `/private/tmp/openclaw-pr-88913-proof-*/home/.openclaw/extensions`, wrote the persisted installed-plugin index with `writePersistedInstalledPluginIndexSync(...)`, then called `listOpenClawPluginManifestMetadata()`, `isNonSecretApiKeyMarker(...)`, and the lifecycle-cleared marker path against `OPENCLAW_HOME=<tmp>/home` and `OPENCLAW_DISABLE_BUNDLED_PLUGINS=1`.\n\nEvidence after fix: terminal output from the current-head temp-home proof:\n\n```text\nproof: temp home=<tmp>/home\nproof: enabled manifest discovered=true\nproof: disabled manifest discovered=false\nproof: enabled marker accepted=true\nproof: disabled marker accepted=false\nproof: v2 marker before lifecycle clear=false\nproof: v2 marker after index lifecycle clear=true\nproof: v1 marker after index lifecycle clear=false\n```\n\nObserved result after fix: the enabled installed plugin manifest was discovered and its marker was accepted; the disabled installed plugin manifest was filtered and its marker was rejected; marker lookup stayed process-stable until the installed-index write cleared plugin metadata lifecycle caches, after which the new marker was accepted and the old marker was no longer accepted.\n\nWhat was not tested: no networked marketplace/plugin registry install and no live third-party credentials were used; the proof exercises the installed-plugin index and manifest metadata production path with redacted temp files.\n",
